## Bus Services Act 2025 Implications

Market concentration is a central consideration under the Bus Services Act 2025. LTAs seeking franchising powers must demonstrate, among other things, that the current market structure is not delivering outcomes consistent with the Local Transport Plan. A high HHI — particularly combined with evidence of service deterioration or equity gaps — strengthens the proportionality case for franchising.

Under Enhanced Partnerships, high concentration creates a risk of operator hold-out, where the dominant operator resists partnership commitments that would reduce their commercial freedom. Franchising removes this risk by replacing commercial negotiation with contractual specification.

## Operator Landscape

{% if hhi > 2500 -%}
The highly concentrated market in {{ region_name }} reflects the national pattern of consolidation following deregulation in 1986. The combination of high entry barriers (vehicle costs, depot requirements, regulatory compliance) and network effects that favour incumbents has driven consolidation in most non-metropolitan areas. The Bus Services Act 2025 represents the first legislative opportunity since deregulation to structurally reshape this market.
{%- else -%}
The {{ "moderately competitive" if hhi < 2500 else "moderately concentrated" }} market in {{ region_name }} provides some protection against monopoly outcomes. However, even competitive markets can fail to serve commercially unattractive routes — the equity and coverage gaps documented elsewhere in this analysis demonstrate that market competition alone does not guarantee equitable service.
